{{Infobox minister | name = Davor Štern | honorific-suffix = | image = | imagesize = | office = [[Ministry of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship (Croatia)|Minister of Economy]] | term_start = 7 November 1995 | term_end = 14 April 1997 | primeminister= [[Zlatko Mateša]] | predecessor = Zlatko Mateša | successor = [[Nenad Porges]] | office2 = | predecessor2 = | successor2 = | term_start2 = | term_end2 = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1947|06|18|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Zagreb]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]], (now [[Croatia]]) | death_date = | death_place = | party = [[Croatian Social Liberal Party]] (2006–2010)<ref>[http://www.jutarnji.hr/davor-stern-i-sinisa-srzic-pristupili-hsls-u/230338/ Davor Štern i Siniša Srzić pristupili HSLS-u]</ref><ref>[http://www.jutarnji.hr/odlazi-i-davor-stern--hsls-nije--obranio-poduzetnicku-slobodu/846659/ Odlazi i Štern: HSLS izabrao loš tajming za napuštanje koalicije], [[Jutarnji list]]</ref> | alma_mater = [[University of Zagreb]] | residence = | spouse = | children = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = [[Croats|Croat]] }}
'''Davor Štern''' (born 18 June 1947 in Zagreb, Croatia) is a former [[Ministry of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship (Croatia)|Minister of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship]] in the [[Croatian Government]], businessman and entrepreneur.
==Background and education== Štern was born in [[Zagreb]] on 18 June 1947. His father was a [[History of the Jews in Hungary|Hungarian Jew]] and his mother was from [[Šestanovac]], [[Croatia]]. Štern himself was raised [[Jew]]ish.<ref name=ncl>{{cite news |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/20379/udario-bih-goldsteina-da-nas-nisu-razdvojili |title=Udario bih Goldsteina da nas nisu razdvojili |trans-title=I would have hit Goldstein were we not pulled apart |publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |author=Plamenko Cvitić |date=12 September 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |archivedate=7 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68ysKsTw8?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/20379/udario-bih-goldsteina-da-nas-nisu-razdvojili |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/tako-smo-se-zaljubili-da-smo-se-morali-ozeniti-jos-kao-studenti/200599/ |title=Tako smo se zaljubili da smo se morali oženiti još kao studenti |publisher=[[Jutarnji list]] |work=www.jutarnji.hr |language=Croatian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016075429/http://www.jutarnji.hr/tako-smo-se-zaljubili-da-smo-se-morali-ozeniti-jos-kao-studenti/200599/ |archivedate=2012-10-16 |df= }}</ref> He is fluent in English, Russian, Italian, German, Hebrew and Croatian. He graduated in 1967 at the [[University of Zagreb]] (faculty of Petroleum, Geology and Mining). Štern is a member of the Jewish community in Zagreb.<ref name=ncl />
==Career== After graduation, in 1972 he worked for [[INA (company)|INA]] and in 1973 he was hired by Yugoslav oil pipeline. From 1976 until 1982 he worked as director of imports in INA – Commerce. In 1982 he was appointed as a branch director of INA in [[Moscow]], he worked in that position until 1986. From 1986 until 1991 he worked as director of [[Philipp Brothers|Philipp Brothers – Salomon Brothers]] representative office in Moscow. He worked as a branch director of [[Glencore]] from 1991 until 1993. From 1993 until 1994 he worked as director of Trade Consulting in [[Graz]], Austria. He was a Deputy [[Ministry of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship (Croatia)|Minister of Economy]] from 1994 until 1995, when he was appointed as a Minister of Economy. He held that office until 1997. In 1997 he became a general manager of INA – Oil Industry d.d. and he remained on that position until 2000. In 2001 he returned to Moscow as advisor to a president of [[TNK-BP]]. He remained there until 2004 and since then he has been a director of Zagreb Trade Consulting Company.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/davor-stern--sagradimo-nuklearku-u-obrovcu/240318/ |title=Davor Štern: Sagradimo nuklearku u Obrovcu |publisher=Jutarnji list |work=www.jutarnji.hr |language=Croatian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100224011015/http://www.jutarnji.hr/davor-stern--sagradimo-nuklearku-u-obrovcu/240318/ |archivedate=2010-02-24 |df= }}</ref> On 21 October 2010 Štern was named a member of INA supervisory board.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/ivan-suker-odlazi--davor-stern-se-vraca-u-vrh-ine-nakon-deset-godina/897014/|title=Smjena u NO Ine: Šuker odlazi, Štern se vraća nakon 10 godina|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|work=www.jutarnji.hr|language=Croatian}}</ref>
Štern is one of the Croatia's wealthiest people, with estimated net worth of €43 million according to the list from 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/33748/50-najbogatijih-hrvata |title=50 najbogatijih Hrvata |trans-title=50 richest Croats |publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |author=Mislav Šimatović |date=24 April 2007 |accessdate=9 July 2012 |archivedate=9 July 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/692M9P5RP?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/33748/50-najbogatijih-hrvata |df= }}</ref>
Štern also serves as Honorary Consul General of the [[Philippines]] in [[Croatia]].
==Philanthropy== Štern is known for his [[philanthropy]]. He always preferred anonymous donations over those that are visible to the public.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://globus.jutarnji.hr/zivot/i-mi-bismo-rado-darovali-milijune |title=I mi bismo rado darovali milijune |work=[[Globus (weekly)|Globus]] |language=Croatian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918122351/http://globus.jutarnji.hr/zivot/i-mi-bismo-rado-darovali-milijune |archivedate=2010-09-18 |df= }}</ref>
